{"role": "user", "content": "User laminated-wire posted:\n\"@black-hertz, I've been reading up on quantum entanglement, and I'm still\nstruggling to understand how it's possible for two particles to be\ninstantaneously connected, regardless of the distance between them.\nIs there a specific experiment or demonstration that can help illustrate\nthis concept?\"\nUser black-hertz posted:\n\"@laminated-wire, a great example of this is the Bell's theorem experiment.\nIt demonstrates the non-locality of entangled particles, even when they\nare separated by large distances.\"\nUser laminated-wire posted:\n\"That sounds interesting. I'll definitely look into the Bell's theorem experiment.\nThank you for your help, @black-hertz. I really appreciate it.\"\nUser moderator posted:"}

